A Czech Referee Fights for the Seabed
It is approaching an electronic wall map, on which Australia and the adjacent marine areas are represented.
Now, he is not interested in the continent, but in a small point lost in the blue of the ocean.
"The island belongs to Australia, as does the adjacent seabed.
This area, however, is as large as the continent itself," said Italian lawyer Luigi Santosuosso, who is part of the 30-member team of the UN Division for Oceans and the Law of the Sea.
Its leader, the director of the division, the Czech jurist Václav Mikulka, follows the presentation and completes it from time to time.
The ardor at work and enthusiasm characterize the prevailing atmosphere.
The seabed hides a world little known until now, rich in natural resources.
Oil, minerals and other mineral resources can be found there, but also living organisms that are currently unknown, which may hold the key to the development of a cancer drug.
A fund wider than the land
Nowadays, coastal states have begun to aspire vehemently to new underwater territories.
According to a UN convention, they are in fact availing themselves of their rights, on which they agreed in 1982 in Montego Bay, Jamaica.
This is mainly the area of the so-called continental shelf, which often extends several hundred kilometers from the coast of the given country.
The latter may, according to the Convention, be entitled exclusively to all the resources of the continental shelf.
"To simplify, continental shelf is considered the part of the seabed and its subsoil, which constitutes a natural extension of the continent under the sea.
It extends beyond the boundaries of the coastal sea, often also beyond the two hundred nautical miles that represent the so-called exclusive economic yone,” explains Mikulka.
The request that the country in question submits to the Commission for the establishment of the external borders of the continental shelf, must be supported by a wide scientific-technical documentation, based on many exploration and costly metering.
It is the result of several years of preparatory work.
"One of our roles is to provide the commission with legal and scientific-technical assistance.
So far, the Commission has dealt with five applications, from Russia, Brazil, Australia, Ireland and New Zealand.
So far, only the last three countries mentioned have been successful," adds Mikulka.
Australia’s success as the first country to significantly expand its underwater holdings has recently made a worldwide impact.
New Zealand, too, has gained territory - the extent of the seabed, which was assigned to it by the commission last week, is 1.6 million square kilometers, which represents the extent of the country multiplied by six.
Both countries have invested millions of dollars in prospecting.
The future benefit they will derive from the exploitation of the seabed will, as they anticipate, be invaluable.
Gradually, other countries will, in turn, submit their applications.
They can do so within ten years of ratifying the Montego Bay Convention.
There, where the continental shelf ends, begins the area of the ocean floor, proclaimed by convention "common heritage of humanity".
There is no longer any state that enjoys an exclusive position.
The right of extraction in this area is granted by an international institution established by convention.
"However, make no mistake, the seabed is not a Klondike," said Director Mikulka, adding that "its areas are clearly defined and their regime is anchored in a contract."
Czechs in the Pacific
A part of the seabed now also belongs to the Czech Republic.
It shares it with other states of the former Eastern bloc within the framework of the common organization "Interoceanmetal".
In 1991, it was granted the status of a so-called "pioneer investor" by the Convention, as well as by investors from a few other States.
It has the right of extraction in the ClarionClipperton zone in the Pacific Ocean, located between Mexico, the Hawaiian Islands and Kiribati.
The area prospected by the investor slightly exceeds the area of the former Czechoslovakia.
The bottom is hectic, it is a kind of underwater replica of the Tatra.
“It is possible to extract it on an expanse with a total area of 75,000 square kilometers.
The area represents a deposit rich in polymetallic concretions containing nickel, copper, cobalt and manganese," lists Ind Pakshi Rajan, another lawyer.
Rober Sandev, a Macedonian employee of the division, provides an example of such a concreteness.
It recalls a small potato, or, with a little imagination, the mythical shoem, which, according to legend, animated the Golem.
