The organizers report an increasing number of bookings
This should be a good winter for German travel agencies:
In terms of bookings for the coming months, according to a study, the turnover has increased significantly compared to the previous year - for the winter season, even by more than 30 percent.
Despite the weak economic outlook, Germans’ thirst for travel remains insatiable, according to the study.
In terms of bookings for the winter season, travel agencies recorded sales of more than 31 percent compared to the same period last year, as the German Federation of Travel Agencies (DRV) said Monday in Berlin.
According to the survey of the GfK Market Research Institute, increasing booking numbers already dominate the autumn months.
The sales figure would have risen to about 11 percent more compared to 2007, said the DRV.
The sources of these results are the figures of the GfK, which analyzes monthly booking data from 1,200 travel agencies and makes estimates for the global market.
Travel bookings made since the end of August 2008 would be recorded there.
Due to the low dollar price, travel to the US would be particularly in demand, the DRV said.
There, the increase in bookings would amount to about one-third.
Alongside this, Spain, Turkey and Greece as well as our country would be particularly sought after destinations by the Germans.
Specially organized trips are in high demand, explained DRV President Klaus Laepple.
In view of the rising prices of energy and food products, the costs here would be "easier to calculate for the customer than for an individually arranged trip".
Consumers can save money among other things with early booking discounts or All Inclusive offers, Laepple explained.
The summer months were also very popular so that an increase in sales figures will be recorded again compared to last year - although according to another study, the number of Germans who undertook a trip decreased compared to the previous year.
