Morgan Stanley has announced the entry into the table of Mitsubishi UFJ Financial Group (MUFG), the first bank in Japan, which will disburse nine billion dollars to take 21% of its capital, a new welcomed by a sharp fall in its stock price.
A week after unveiling a provisional deal, the two banks explained that MUFG would buy 9.9% of Morgan Stanley common shares at the unit price of $25.25, a total amount of $3 billion.
The retained price is 19% lower than the book value of the securities at August 31.
MUFG will invest an additional $6 billion in the acquisition of convertible securities with a return of 10% and a conversion price of $31.25.
Morgan Stanley said the overall transaction would be based on an average unit price of $29, or 28% above its current price.
Morgan Stanley was down 6.79% at $23.07 around 5 p.m. GMT.
“This strategic alliance is an important opportunity to accelerate Morgan Stanley’s transition to banking holding status,” said John Mack, CEO of Morgan Stanley.
Morgan Stanley adopted the new statute last week, which should allow it to diversify its activities but put it under the authority of the Federal Reserve.
His alliance with MUFG also confirms that the current financial crisis is forcing the biggest names on Wall Street to adopt a much more cautious attitude than before.
The terms presented on Monday also show that the deal has been modified in recent days: last Monday, Morgan had simply announced that he would sell up to 20% of his shares to Japan for about $8.5 billion.
"A week ago," Toshihide Mizuno, MUFG's executive director, told Tokyo, "we thought the stake would be entirely made up of ordinary shares.
But given the current situation of the economy and the market, we wanted to minimize the risks and cover ourselves."
Based on the weighted average price, MUFG will pay its Morgan Stanley securities 7% below their book value.
And the operation will result in a dilution of about 20% of the profit per share.
The agreement provides that MUFG will be able to convert in one year half of its preferential securities into common shares if the latter are exchanged more than 50% above the conversion price, or about $47, during a given period.
Morgan Stanley assures that the capital provided by MUFG will allow it to seize investment opportunities, strengthen its balance sheet and increase its liquidity.
A spokeswoman for the group declined to elaborate on the strategic plans of the two new allies.
After MUFG’s investment, Morgan Stanley is expected to show a Tier One solvency ratio of around 15%, one of the best in the industry.
Morgan said it had "clearly" eased its balance sheet since the end of August.
The past few weeks have been challenging for the group, which has seen its stock price melt by half as the cost of insurance against a default risk on its debt flew away.
This cost fell on Monday but remained at a high level, around 12%.
Last week, Goldman Sachs, the only other "survivor" of the major Wall Street investment banks after the bankruptcies of Bear Stearns and Lehman Brothers and the takeover of Merrill Lynch, announced it had raised $15 billion, in part from Berkshire Hathaway, the group of Warren Buffett.
Rafael Correa in Quito on Monday.
Re-founding the republic around 21st century socialism.
This is the joint project of Venezuelan Hugo Chávez, Bolivian Evo Morales and Ecuadorian Rafael Correa.
This Sunday, like his counterparts and friends, it was the third to put to the vote a draft new Constitution.
Mission accomplished since 64% of the voters voted "yes" in the referendum, according to official results covering 80% of the votes.
According to these results, the "no" got 28%, 7% of the votes were null and 0.7% were white votes.
In order for the draft Constitution to be adopted, he had to obtain half the votes plus one.
On Sunday, two polls carried out outside the polling stations and a count of a non-governmental organization had announced a broad victory of the "yes", placing it between 63% and 70%.
Rafael Correa claimed the victory of his draft constitution on Sunday night.
"The Constitution has triumphed overwhelmingly," he said, congratulating Ecuadorians at the headquarters of the governorate of Guayaquil, 280 kilometers southwest of Quito.
As of course, Rafael Correa was congratulated by Chávez and Morales but also his Chilean counterpart Michelle Bachelet.
The election, which took place quietly according to the observation mission of the Organization of American States (OAS), focused on a text in 444 points consolidating the "new socialism" defended by the president.
The draft Constitution enshrines the state's power over the economy, reserving it the "development planning" of a country living essentially from the extraction of oil by foreign companies and the currencies sent by its emigrants.
Supported by Correa, who was elected in 2006, the project also grants enhanced powers to the head of state, who will be able to serve up to two consecutive four-year terms and will have the possibility of dissolving the Assembly.
Correa has already announced that he will use this power and run for a new term in February 2009.
The Constitution also consolidates the principle of free health and education services that the President has begun to establish in this country of 13.9 million inhabitants, where 50 per cent of the population lives below the poverty line.
Finally, it provides for the prohibition of the presence of foreign troops, which will end the agreement between Quito and Washington for the use of an Ecuadorian base as a starting point for US anti-drug operations.
19 hostages released in Chad
An Egyptian commando has launched an assault on the kidnappers of the eleven tourists and their eight companions captured ten days ago.
They're in Cairo.
The eleven European tourists and their eight Egyptian escorts held captive for ten days in the desert were brought back safe and sound to the Egyptian capital on Monday afternoon.
In the morning, they were released by an Egyptian commando in Chad.
Apparently in good shape, the hostages arrived at around 3:30 p.m. on board a special aircraft at al-Maza military base, which is attached to Cairo International Airport.
They were immediately transferred, without being able to speak to the press, aboard helicopters to the hospital in Maadi, a residential suburb of Cairo, for examinations.
They are in “good health” and “no ransom has been paid” to the kidnappers, Egyptian Tourism Minister Zoheir Garanna said on the tarmac.
Captured on September 19 during a 4x4 safari at the foot of Mount Ouanat, on the borders of Egypt, Sudan and Libya, this group of hostages had been swept from one hideout to the other by 35 unknown kidnappers.
It includes 11 tourists - five Italians, five Germans and one Romanian - as well as eight Egyptians: two guides, four drivers, a border guard and the director of the agency Aegyptous, organizer of the safari.
An Egyptian security official said 30 Special Forces personnel, carried on board two helicopters, had launched the assault on the night just before dawn.
"An exchange of gunfire occurred, and half of the kidnappers were killed, the others fleeing," the official said, who requested anonymity.
He indicated that 150 members of the Egyptian special forces of the "blitz" unit had been sent in total to Sudan, where they received the support of German and Italian commandos.
Italian diplomat Franco Frattini mentioned from Belgrade, where he is, the role played by secret agents and elements of Italian special forces.
"We must recognize that we have achieved this result thanks to the professionalism and efficiency of our men from the secret services, special forces," he said, without further details.
He also denied the payment of a ransom.
The day before, the Sudanese army claimed to have intercepted during a patrol a 4x4 vehicle in which the kidnappers were, killing six, including the Chadian leader, and arresting two.
The army claimed they were linked to a rebel group in Darfur, the Sudan Liberation Movement-United (SLA-U), which the movement immediately denied.
Letters - The Silent Majority of Culture
A debate on the financing of culture is making headlines and occupying the current election campaign.
I'm fine.
But one area of our cultural life is still forgotten.
Who will stand up to denounce the sums of misery that are granted to small museums, archives, archaeological excavations or national historical sites that starve?
What politician would dare remind the federal government that it neglects its monuments and heritage buildings?
That in Quebec, as in Canada, we do not have real laws that effectively preserve our heritage?
Did you know that the French government spends three and a half million euros on the restoration of the only Château de Chinon in the Loire Valley?
Among our American neighbors, it is written in the Constitution of their country that the protection of heritage is part of the culture of Americans and that this heritage must be protected by all citizens, all elected officials and all government departments, and this, in consultation.
In Quebec, at the Fédération des sociétés d'histoire du Québec, at least 40,000 volunteers grouped in 211 societies of history, heritage, archives and genealogy are concerned with searching history, preserving with three under heaps of private archives and preserving archaeological remains.
They are often the watchdogs of our heritage, protesting with the energy of despair when promoters and policy makers throw their bulldozers at our forgotten stones and cemeteries.
When, a forum for history and heritage?
Benelux governments nationalise part of Fortis bank
The Benelux states are helping the Belgian-Dutch bank, as the first European bank in distress as a result of the snowball effect of the credit market crisis in the United States, by partially nationalizing it.The three countries support, with a sum of 11.2 billion euros, this financial and insurance institution also having interests in Hungary.
This weekend, the Belgian, Luxembourg and Dutch governments agreed, at the highest level, on this case, also appealing to the European Central Bank and the head of competition of the European Commission.
In the euro area, the first major crisis in the context of the international financial crisis, which has been escalating for more than a year, is for Fortis Bank, and from a certain point of view, the decisions that will be taken in the case of this bank will serve as a precedent.
In accordance with the decision taken on Sunday night, the three states will buy back nearly half (to the tune of 49%) of the capital of the bank located in each of the countries.
The bank will undoubtedly sell some of its holdings, including primarily the mainly insurance activities it acquired last year from the Dutch agency ABN Amro.
Last week, Fortis shares began a dizzying fall. In the second half of the week, serious signs of crisis have already been revealed at the bank.
Analysts agree that with its 85,000 employees, the bank is far too big to let go of bankruptcy.
On Friday alone, the company’s shares fell 12 percent to their lowest level of 14 years ago.
Since January, shares have fallen by more than two-thirds of their value.
Taking into account the current value of the shares, the total value of the group’s capital is around 14 billion euros, which, according to the company’s executives, is not realistic.
The company’s management accuses the overseas uncertainty, related to the adoption of the US $700 billion bailout, of being the cause of the fall in Fortis shares.
On Monday, papers already benefited from a slight increase.
On Friday, Filip Dierckx was appointed head of the bank, as the new CEO.
The financial body was also looking for private acquirers, but has not yet received a proposal on the merits.
Previously, the Belgian government announced that investors should not worry, they were not going to lose their money.
No panic was felt in the bank’s customer circle and no agency was stormed.
In Hungary, Fortis has independent agencies and has also acquired leasing companies.
A fox in the chicken coop
In America, life and health insurance companies frequently refuse to sign an insurance contract with a candidate, based on information about their drug purchases.
Information protection experts fear that the data market will become uncontrollable.
"There are data protection programs that bind the use of information regarding the prescription of medicines, in any case, to the consent of the data subject.
This kind of program has to be in independent hands, otherwise it’s like entrusting your henhouse to a fox,” Richard Dicket, the creator of the program used to manage prescription drugs, told the Washington Post.
Insurance companies make the insurance premium and the insured capital in case of damage dependent on the health of the client who presents himself, and if they feel that the risk is too great, they do not even insure it.
In the past, they sent candidates for medical examination, and they did not sign an insurance contract with them until they were aware of the results.
For the past ten years, Dick has found a much cheaper procedure: from an identification number, he easily obtains from pharmacies, data about the person's drug purchases in the past eighteen months. From this, the program determines itself, what disease the person suffers from and what is his state of health.
For example, if that person regularly buys high doses of cholesterol-lowering, this refers to an extremely high level of fat in the blood, which immediately puts them in a higher risk category.
Several versions of this program are in circulation. Some at the same time determine a risk coefficient, so there is not much left to do to the insurer aside from paperwork. However, tiny problems may still appear.
Among the disadvantages of this program is the fact that a drug can be used for different purposes. For example, some mixtures can be used against migraine or hot flashes, but can also be effective against depression.
The latter is seen by insurers as an aggravating risk factor, while the others do not.
Companies have developed in the research and analysis of data, they must ask the patient for permission before collecting the necessary information from the pharmacy.
From now on, they are forced to do so by the authorities, even if they have not been sanctioned for their failures in the past.
Recently, some companies have also been processing the results of laboratory analyses and linking them with data on drug use, thus being able to provide an even more accurate picture of patients' health status.
More and more companies have access to data, and at the same time, control of use is becoming increasingly difficult.
There is a separate law on the protection of medical data, but its scope of action extends only to practitioners and insurers.
A bill to enlarge the circle of control of the authorities on companies specializing in the provision of data is currently before Congress.
Dick Richard acknowledges that this is not enough and that is why he has further developed his program, which would condition the transmission of data to the exclusive agreement of the data subject.
It is another question of whether the person concerned is really free to give his consent or not, since if he refuses, the insurance companies do not sign an insurance contract with him.
Thus, in the end, chickens depend on the fox’s benevolence.
The global menu of Marseille
The European Union and India are doubling their trade.
Since the European Union and India are very important trading partners for each other, this topic also dominated the agenda of this ninth summit alongside the other problems, largely global.
Today, there will also be a France-India summit, where cooperation in the field of atomic energy will be discussed.
The European Union recognizes that India is an emerging democratic power that should be given a broader say in international affairs, but member countries have yet to agree on their support in New Delhi for its candidacy as a permanent member of the UN Security Council.
They did not dwell too much on this question, yesterday, at this 9th summit held in Marseille.
The French President, Nicolas Sarkozy, as well as the current President of the Union, as well as the President of the Commission José Manuel Barroso and the Head of Diplomacy, Javier Solana, welcomed the Indian Prime Minister, Manmohan Singh, with whom they agreed that in five years, they would double the trade, which means an increase of a good hundred billion euros.
Taking into account that between 2000 and 2007, trade in goods increased from 25 billion to 55 billion, this does not seem to be an overly ambitious target.
In this sense, they have legally harmonized the 26 bilateral conventions with India concerning civilian flights, thus allowing air trade to flourish in the future.
India would like to sign a free trade agreement with the EU by the end of 2009.
Sarkozy promised to speed up the negotiations.
The aim is to balance the situation with India, the EU's largest trading partner, on the one hand, and New Delhi, on the other, which ranks only ninth among EU partners.
The summit devoted its attention to global affairs.
The situation in Afghanistan and Pakistan has been strongly condemned, as well as all forms of terrorism, and the urgency of holding a United Nations conference on this issue has been raised.
Completion of the Doha trade cycle was also called for, although both play a large part in the current failure.
The EU has confirmed that it remains faithful to the energy and climate agenda, including its desire to reduce its releases of toxic materials by at least 20% until 2020.
India also agreed on this point, as well as on the need to pass a global market at next year's climate conference, and reduce greenhouse gas emissions by fifty percent by 2050.
They would also like to prevent rising food prices, and supported the convening of an international working meeting to discuss the financial crisis.
The Indian head of state is visiting the French capital today, where during a bilateral meeting, he is preparing to sign an agreement on the peaceful use of atomic energy.
In Paris, it is hoped that French companies will receive orders worth 20 billion euros for the construction of Indian atomic reactors.
According to the news agency, the agreement would be for 15 years.
In Frankfurt, more than three hundred Italian publishers
Strong presence of Italian publishers at the Frankfurt International Book Fair.
More than three hundred Italian publishers present at the 60th edition of the Buchmesse, the most important international event in the exchange of rights.
The Frankfurt International Book Fair awaits for this edition, more than 7 thousand exhibitors from 101 different countries that will occupy the 171,790 square meters of the Fair with more than 403 thousand titles on display, and Turkey as guest of honor.
It will be the Undersecretary of the Ministry of Cultural Property and Activities, Francesco Maria Giro, who will represent the Italian Government, during the inauguration ceremony of the Italian Butterfly: indeed, Italy will be present in an institutional way, with a Point Italy- 264 square meters of exhibition space.
It will be followed by the meeting with the press in the Room Struktur, at the butterfly 5.0 of the Buchmesse: an opportunity to present the figures, trends and prospects on the position of the edition in Italy.
According to the data, the importance of foreign author books is gradually decreasing in relation to the total Italian production, and in particular, in relation to that for adults and children.
Found the plane of Steve Fossett, the billionaire disappeared a year ago.
The wreckage of Steve Fosset's plane, the billionaire who disappeared on September 3, 2007, while flying over the Nevada desert, has been found.
The debris was found on a plateau 3,000 meters above sea level in the Sierra Nevada area of Mammonth Lakes, on the California-Nevada border.
Inside the plane, however, no human remains.
Madera County Sheriff John Anderson said: “The plane has been located, we have sent a team, and now we have confirmation that this is the one that Steve Fosset was traveling on the day he disappeared.”
The sheriff said no human remains were found on or around the plane.
In February, the 63-year-old billionaire was deemed dead.
The U.S. Bureau of Transportation Safety (NTSB) reported that a few hours after the wreckage was located, a team of investigators sent to the scene identified the aircraft: it was the Bellanca 8kcab, which disappeared on September 3, 2007, when Fosset took off from Yerington, Nevada for a three-hour flight.
Yesterday, still in California, not far from the Nevada border, some personal belongings of Fosset were found by a couple around their home in Mammoth Lakes.
These are two documents bearing the name Fosset, both issued by the Federal Aviation Administration of Illinois, cash and a sweater.
Fossett's search was interrupted a month after his disappearance.
The billionaire had earned a place in history thanks to a long series of records.
By the sixth attempt, he had become in 2002 the first man to complete the round the world in an aerostatic balloon: two weeks of solo flight.
Three years later, he had circled the world by plane and non-stop.
Among all these records, also that of flying at 15,445 meters high, in the Andes, but with a co-pilot.
Glk, the ad you're not expecting.
An unusual 4x4 with an original and well-defined design, marked lines, wide surfaces and sharp angles.
This is, in summary, Glk, the last born of the off-road "compact" of the house of the star, with which Mercedes-Benz has tried to give a wind of novelty in this sector.
Precisely because of its non-standard content, unexpected and unconventional will be the communication that will accompany the launch of the 4x4 Glk, available in Mercedes-Benz showrooms, from October 17th.
Thus, the hype that will accompany the beginning of the new car will give rise to an unprecedented mode of communication, through a futuristic campaign of 3D displays, used for the first time in Italy by an automobile brand.
A project of maxi displays, articulated in three different phases, that will dominate the heart of Milanese shopping, Corso Como, until November 15.
The first phase of this new type of communication involves the presentation of the car in stereoscopic vision, and thanks to special glasses distributed around Corso Como, it will be possible to see the new 4x4 in almost real dimensions and in three-dimensional format.
Indeed, we will have the impression that when looking at the image, the car comes out of the poster.
Then, through the use of the innovative Elimina8 technology, the new Glk will be illuminated according to the spots, in all its details, and then recomposed into a single image.
It is obvious that with this advertising, Mercedes is trying to introduce something new in the stereotypical field of motorsport communication.
Will it succeed with this formula to arouse the interest of future buyers? We will see well.
